1
00:00:00,720 --> 00:00:06,160
﻿Chinese political culture is strange, to say the 
least. China has made unbelievably fast progress  

2
00:00:06,160 --> 00:00:10,400
in almost every area of society in the past 
couple decades, by basically every observable  

3
00:00:10,400 --> 00:00:14,840
metric. But, that isn’t to say everyone in 
China is perfectly content with the country,  

4
00:00:14,840 --> 00:00:19,440
or that other more abstract problems haven’t 
appeared in recent times. Political repression  

5
00:00:19,440 --> 00:00:22,840
and economic stagnation for the middle 
class have led to discontent and a  

6
00:00:22,840 --> 00:00:26,800
nostalgia for China’s recent past.
China’s advances have come at the cost of  

7
00:00:26,800 --> 00:00:31,000
increased government oversight and meddling in the 
lives of its citizens, leading many to yearn for  

8
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:35,080
times of comparative freedom, even if people were 
poorer and the country was less developed during  

9
00:00:35,080 --> 00:00:40,760
those times. One leader has come to embody and 
symbolize this spirit, that being Jiang Zemin.  

10
00:00:40,760 --> 00:00:44,680
Jiang was a fascinating and unique person, both 
in his life and his political career.
 

11
00:00:44,680 --> 00:00:48,400
Before we get into it, I’ll mention that sources 
about Jiang Zemin tend to be pretty biased,  

12
00:00:48,400 --> 00:00:52,640
either for or against him. There isn’t a lot of 
neutral discussion like there is about someone  

13
00:00:52,640 --> 00:00:56,680
like Deng Xiaoping or Hua Guofeng. Doesn’t 
help that he was a decently controversial  

14
00:00:56,680 --> 00:01:00,280
guy who only died recently. I’ve pulled from a 
lot of different sources, and tried to follow  

15
00:01:00,280 --> 00:01:04,040
the most cohesive and even-keeled narrative, 
and stick to the facts as best I can.
 

16
00:01:04,040 --> 00:01:08,760
Jiang Zemin was born on August 17th, 
1926, in Yangzhou, in eastern China,  

17
00:01:08,760 --> 00:01:13,280
to a large, generally well off family. From 
a young age, he enjoyed reading and poetry,  

18
00:01:13,280 --> 00:01:18,120
and became a fan of French and Russian literature. 
His family wasn’t very political, and he developed  

19
00:01:18,120 --> 00:01:22,160
his early communist sympathies as part of student 
movements in Yangzhou. Part of what spurred  

20
00:01:22,160 --> 00:01:26,520
his early political beliefs were the Japanese 
incursions into China throughout the 1930s.
 

21
00:01:26,520 --> 00:01:30,480
Chiang Kai-shek, the military dictator of 
China, saw the communist movement in the  

22
00:01:30,480 --> 00:01:34,520
country as a bigger threat than the literal 
empire encroaching on his country. Famously,  

23
00:01:34,520 --> 00:01:38,800
he said, “The Japanese are a disease of the skin, 
the Communists are a disease of the heart.” A  

24
00:01:38,800 --> 00:01:43,920
few army officers arrested him in late 1936, and 
demanded he seek an alliance with the communists,  

25
00:01:43,920 --> 00:01:48,120
which he eventually did. The most notable 
officer was the general Zhang Xueliang, who  

26
00:01:48,120 --> 00:01:52,960
Jiang Zemin praised for this in an essay he wrote 
for a high school entrance exam in 1937.
 

27
00:01:52,960 --> 00:01:57,960
Also in 1937, Yangzhou fell to the Japanese. 
Yangzhou was spared much of the brutality  

28
00:01:57,960 --> 00:02:02,200
characteristic of Japanese occupation, but Jiang 
and his family were still affected. He had to  

29
00:02:02,200 --> 00:02:06,600
quit school, and many men in his family had been 
conscripted earlier and were away at war. School  

30
00:02:06,600 --> 00:02:11,480
resumed in late 1939, now with the Japanese 
language as a required class. He apparently  

31
00:02:11,480 --> 00:02:15,200
hated this class, which is a little strange 
for someone who would later learn at least  

32
00:02:15,200 --> 00:02:19,280
five languages. Jiang later stated his Japanese 
would have been better if he wasn’t forced to  

33
00:02:19,280 --> 00:02:24,160
learn it under a military occupation.
He attended college in Nanjing in 1943, later  

34
00:02:24,160 --> 00:02:28,400
transferring to a school in Shanghai, all still 
under Japanese occupation. Throughout his college  

35
00:02:28,400 --> 00:02:32,520
years, he participated in many pro-communist 
protests, against both the Japanese, and later,  

36
00:02:32,520 --> 00:02:38,160
the Nationalist government. He graduated in 1947 
with a degree in electrical engineering. Jiang  

37
00:02:38,160 --> 00:02:42,200
worked in various factories around Shanghai 
through the end of the ‘40s and early ‘50s,  

38
00:02:42,200 --> 00:02:46,480
everything from an ice cream factory to a soap 
making plant. After the People’s Liberation Army  

39
00:02:46,480 --> 00:02:49,840
gained control of the city in the midst of the 
civil war, he also joined formally joined the  

40
00:02:49,840 --> 00:02:54,280
communist party. He was made party secretary 
for various industries and factories throughout  

41
00:02:54,280 --> 00:02:58,360
the Shanghai area, dealing with communicating 
between the government and the factories.
 

42
00:02:58,360 --> 00:03:03,200
In 1953, China set out to build their first 
automotive factory, in Changchun, with Soviet  

43
00:03:03,200 --> 00:03:08,200
help. In 1954, Jiang was sent to Changchun to help 
with the construction efforts. He was selected  

44
00:03:08,200 --> 00:03:12,240
to be one of seven hundred technicians sent to 
the Soviet Union to learn from an existing car  

45
00:03:12,240 --> 00:03:16,240
factory in Moscow. He was enrolled in a language 
school in Changchun, where he quickly learned  

46
00:03:16,240 --> 00:03:21,760
Russian. He spent most of 1955 and ‘56 in Moscow, 
learning how to run a car plant. He returned to  

47
00:03:21,760 --> 00:03:25,840
the Changchun plant in 1957, just in time for 
the first trucks to come off the line.
 

48
00:03:25,840 --> 00:03:30,000
He worked at the factory for five years, until 
he could leverage a political connection, Wang  

49
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:33,960
Daohan, a friend from college, to get a job 
back in Shanghai, as director of an electronics  

50
00:03:33,960 --> 00:03:37,960
research institute. One of his main objectives 
was to find international partners to help  

51
00:03:37,960 --> 00:03:42,360
develop China’s domestic electronics industry. 
As part of this, he was sent to Japan, via Hong  

52
00:03:42,360 --> 00:03:45,880
Kong. He was very impressed with both of these 
places, and hoped to apply the principles that  

53
00:03:45,880 --> 00:03:50,040
made them successful back home in China.
He continued managing the research institute,  

54
00:03:50,040 --> 00:03:54,040
generally unaffected by the chaos and upheaval 
of the Cultural Revolution and the ‘60s in  

55
00:03:54,040 --> 00:03:57,520
China. Jiang got through it better than many, 
but he still had quite the ordeal during these  

56
00:03:57,520 --> 00:04:01,440
years. For his interest in foreign languages 
and literature, he was accused of being a  

57
00:04:01,440 --> 00:04:05,600
supporter of foreigners, and wanting to betray 
China. His ties with the Soviet Union didn’t  

58
00:04:05,600 --> 00:04:09,360
help either, since Sino-Soviet relations had 
completely collapsed by this point.
 

59
00:04:09,360 --> 00:04:13,320
Jiang was sent to a special school for 
political correction. The curriculum  

60
00:04:13,320 --> 00:04:17,600
consisted of a year of intensive labor on 
a farm. He raised pigs and harvested wheat,  

61
00:04:17,600 --> 00:04:22,280
eventually clearing all charges against him. 
He was deemed “rehabilitated” in 1970, and got  

62
00:04:22,280 --> 00:04:26,760
a job in Beijing, working for the foreign affairs 
section of the Ministry of the Machine Industries,  

63
00:04:26,760 --> 00:04:30,440
his first serious government position.
China had a pretty short friends list in the  

64
00:04:30,440 --> 00:04:33,800
early ‘70s, one of which was Romania, 
which was trying to distance themselves  

65
00:04:33,800 --> 00:04:38,400
from the Soviet Union. To this end, they sent 
a request to China for technical assistance in  

66
00:04:38,400 --> 00:04:42,960
constructing fifteen machinery factories. Jiang 
Zemin was selected to lead the Chinese delegation,  

67
00:04:42,960 --> 00:04:47,560
and went through a course to learn Romanian. He 
spent two years in Romania, advising the Romanians  

68
00:04:47,560 --> 00:04:51,640
on the construction and operations of their 
factories. He later said he enjoyed the trip,  

69
00:04:51,640 --> 00:04:56,200
and found Romania to be a welcoming place.
Jiang’s next major job was as part of a working  

70
00:04:56,200 --> 00:05:01,200
group to restore order in Shanghai in the 
chaotic aftermath of Mao’s death in 1976.  

71
00:05:01,200 --> 00:05:05,080
Jiang’s task was to repair and strengthen 
transportation and industry in the Shanghai  

72
00:05:05,080 --> 00:05:09,000
area. His job mostly became firing people 
who had jobs they weren’t qualified for,  

73
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:13,920
that were making things inefficient. He kept 
this managerial job until 1979, when China  

74
00:05:13,920 --> 00:05:18,120
made a major policy shift in establishing 
Special Economic Zones, or SEZs.
 

75
00:05:18,120 --> 00:05:22,200
This policy allowed for the promotion of many 
technically minded and politically savvy people,  

76
00:05:22,200 --> 00:05:26,880
including Jiang, who was made vice minister of 
the whole SEZ project. He was also elected to the  

77
00:05:26,880 --> 00:05:30,760
People’s Political Consultative Conference, 
a governmental body in China that oversees  

78
00:05:30,760 --> 00:05:34,600
many aspects of society that are outside the 
direct purview of the Communist Party.
 

79
00:05:34,600 --> 00:05:39,160
Jiang’s task with the SEZs was to create economic 
growth, while maintaining social stability and  

80
00:05:39,160 --> 00:05:43,720
party control in the zones. The main source of 
economic growth would be foreign investment, and  

81
00:05:43,720 --> 00:05:48,160
in 1980, Jiang headed a delegation that visited 
twelve countries in Asia, Europe, and North  

82
00:05:48,160 --> 00:05:52,800
America. The trip was mostly unsuccessful, with 
no foreign countries or companies committing to  

83
00:05:52,800 --> 00:05:57,080
anything. Jiang was still inspired by what he saw, 
and remarked that Singapore and Ireland’s free  

84
00:05:57,080 --> 00:06:02,000
trade models could be applied to the SEZs.
SEZs were still fairly unpopular at the highest  

85
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:05,200
levels of government, but he was able 
to narrowly secure support for the idea  

86
00:06:05,200 --> 00:06:09,120
with a presentation he gave in front of the 
National People’s Congress. The presentation  

87
00:06:09,120 --> 00:06:13,440
was described as “logical” and “humorous,” 
leading Deng Xiaoping, the new leader of China,  

88
00:06:13,440 --> 00:06:18,120
to vocalize his support for Jiang. Jiang was given 
conditional approval to go ahead with his plans,  

89
00:06:18,120 --> 00:06:22,360
and he was allowed to draft policy for the Xiamen 
Special Economic Zone, now making him one of the  

90
00:06:22,360 --> 00:06:26,320
most important lawmakers in China.
This job didn’t last, and he lost it when  

91
00:06:26,320 --> 00:06:31,640
the economic ministries of China were reorganized 
and consolidated in 1982. Thankfully for him, the  

92
00:06:31,640 --> 00:06:35,880
government created the Ministry of the Electronics 
Industry shortly after, and he was made party  

93
00:06:35,880 --> 00:06:40,560
secretary of the ministry after an interview with 
the premier of China, Zhao Ziyang. He was promoted  

94
00:06:40,560 --> 00:06:44,640
to full minister just a short time later. He 
learned this while he was visiting America,  

95
00:06:44,640 --> 00:06:49,440
via a friend, hurriedly leaving a dinner party to 
call the embassy to confirm his promotion.
 

96
00:06:49,440 --> 00:06:54,280
This was during his 1983 visit to the US, where he 
met with various electronics and computer company  

97
00:06:54,280 --> 00:06:59,080
executives, visited universities, and politicians. 
He even met with President Reagan briefly,  

98
00:06:59,080 --> 00:07:04,000
where they exchanged jokes. Jiang reportedly asked 
Reagan why the US won’t export many electronics  

99
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:07,760
and computers to China, to which Reagan responded 
that they were worried about them being used for  

100
00:07:07,760 --> 00:07:12,760
military purposes. Jiang followed up by asking 
why the US was fine with exporting wheat to China,  

101
00:07:12,760 --> 00:07:16,960
after all, China feeds their soldiers with it. 
Reagan reportedly laughed at this joke.
 

102
00:07:16,960 --> 00:07:20,920
After returning to China, he faced a difficult 
challenge managing an electronics industry that  

103
00:07:20,920 --> 00:07:25,840
was more than ten years behind in most aspects. 
He somewhat successfully reorganized the industry,  

104
00:07:25,840 --> 00:07:29,680
closing inefficient factories, modernizing 
the remaining ones, and integrating research  

105
00:07:29,680 --> 00:07:33,520
better with the manufacturing. After his 
visit to America, he knew how important  

106
00:07:33,520 --> 00:07:37,560
computers would become, and helped create some 
of China’s first software development teams.  

107
00:07:37,560 --> 00:07:41,160
His efforts led to an eightfold increase 
in China’s electronics production.
 

108
00:07:41,160 --> 00:07:45,200
Jiang worked to cultivate a good image of the 
reformed electronics industry, and maybe more  

109
00:07:45,200 --> 00:07:50,520
importantly, a good image of himself. In one case, 
he visited Chen Yun, a respected elder statesman,  

110
00:07:50,520 --> 00:07:54,680
with a printed circuit board and a microprocessor, 
using a microscope to show him the intricacies of  

111
00:07:54,680 --> 00:07:59,120
their designs. The visit was reported on by the 
People’s Daily, who highlighted it as an example  

112
00:07:59,120 --> 00:08:03,280
of how foreign advancements and tech didn’t have 
to clash with the country’s domestic politics and  

113
00:08:03,280 --> 00:08:08,360
goals. This was great for Jiang, a Western-minded 
politician who seemed to find more value outside  

114
00:08:08,360 --> 00:08:12,360
the country than in it, he would have to 
constantly buoy his domestic reputation.
 

115
00:08:12,360 --> 00:08:16,160
Jiang did well in his position as minister of 
electronics, but the incessant power struggles  

116
00:08:16,160 --> 00:08:20,120
and bureaucracy common in Chinese politics was 
beginning to wear on him, and he was looking for  

117
00:08:20,120 --> 00:08:24,440
a more low-key assignment. Wang Daohan, 
his old political connection and friend,  

118
00:08:24,440 --> 00:08:28,520
was mayor of Shanghai, and wasn’t doing a great 
job. Shanghai was only growing at about half  

119
00:08:28,520 --> 00:08:31,520
the rate of the rest of the country’s economy, 
pretty bad for what is generally considered the  

120
00:08:31,520 --> 00:08:35,880
financial capitol of the country. Zhao Ziyang 
and Jiang Zemin visited Shanghai to talk with  

121
00:08:35,880 --> 00:08:40,320
Wang Daohan about potentially replacing him. 
Wang Daohan wasn’t happy with his job either,  

122
00:08:40,320 --> 00:08:43,560
and an agreement was reached to replace 
him with Jiang in the near future.
 

123
00:08:43,560 --> 00:08:47,480
Jiang started his term as mayor with a press 
conference, taking questions from reporters,  

124
00:08:47,480 --> 00:08:51,400
instead of the traditional speech. He stated 
that Shanghai’s modernization would be based  

125
00:08:51,400 --> 00:08:56,160
around three “pillars,” infrastructure, foreign 
investment, and technology. Jiang was known at  

126
00:08:56,160 --> 00:09:00,320
this time for his frequent casual visits to 
many areas of the city. He was known to stop  

127
00:09:00,320 --> 00:09:04,160
random people on the street for their opinions 
on various problems in the city, he even helped  

128
00:09:04,160 --> 00:09:08,080
with work at the dockyards occasionally.
He implemented various free market reforms,  

129
00:09:08,080 --> 00:09:12,120
as China was doing as a whole at the time, 
which led to some social instability. Prices  

130
00:09:12,120 --> 00:09:15,320
had stayed basically the same for thirty 
years, and now they had increased by at  

131
00:09:15,320 --> 00:09:19,840
least twenty percent for most items. This led 
to some minor protests, nothing too crazy,  

132
00:09:19,840 --> 00:09:23,440
and Jiang was able to talk them down easily, 
but it was a sign of things to come.
 

133
00:09:23,440 --> 00:09:27,280
Jiang was successful in raising funds from 
international investors for improving the city,  

134
00:09:27,280 --> 00:09:31,320
securing over three billion dollars. Projects 
funded with the money included expanding the  

135
00:09:31,320 --> 00:09:35,920
airport, metro system, and water infrastructure, 
as well as importing food from other regions to  

136
00:09:35,920 --> 00:09:40,760
stabilize food prices. He even got to meet 
the queen when she visited Shanghai in 1986,  

137
00:09:40,760 --> 00:09:44,720
with Jiang personally overseeing her itinerary 
and organizing various events.
 

138
00:09:44,720 --> 00:09:48,120
Jiang met a lot of people as mayor, 
everyone from Deng Xiaoping and down,  

139
00:09:48,120 --> 00:09:52,280
pretty much. He gave a lot of attention to these 
visitors, in one case personally delivering a  

140
00:09:52,280 --> 00:09:56,960
cake to an official who turned 80 years old, 
precisely at midnight. Trust me, not even in  

141
00:09:56,960 --> 00:10:01,320
the top ten weirdest things Jiang did during his 
career. He got to meet and build a relationship  

142
00:10:01,320 --> 00:10:05,480
with basically everyone in Chinese politics, since 
leaders during this time liked to escape Beijing  

143
00:10:05,480 --> 00:10:09,480
winters in Shanghai. He got to spend a lot of 
time with Deng Xiaoping, since he had a habit of  

144
00:10:09,480 --> 00:10:13,520
visiting Shanghai every Chinese New Year.
The latter half of the ‘80s would be a fairly  

145
00:10:13,520 --> 00:10:17,880
trying time for the country, probably the biggest 
period of danger the Communist Party ever faced.  

146
00:10:17,880 --> 00:10:22,480
Top leadership in the country was blindsided by 
major student protests in Beijing in 1985, mainly  

147
00:10:22,480 --> 00:10:27,240
against corrupt officials. Hu Yaobang, general 
secretary of the party at the time and one of the  

148
00:10:27,240 --> 00:10:31,120
major proponents of Deng Xiaoping’s reforms, 
hastily put out a statement supporting the  

149
00:10:31,120 --> 00:10:35,280
protesters. Hu acknowledged and agreed with the 
protesters’ concerns, mainly the need for younger  

150
00:10:35,280 --> 00:10:39,680
politicians and clamping down on corruption. 
Deng also gave Hu limited approval to try some  

151
00:10:39,680 --> 00:10:43,760
of his envisioned political reforms.
This whole debacle led to some fairly nasty  

152
00:10:43,760 --> 00:10:47,200
top-level infighting in Beijing, which 
Jiang wanted to avoid in Shanghai,  

153
00:10:47,200 --> 00:10:51,920
which was facing similar protests. Protests broke 
out at most of Shanghai’s universities, including  

154
00:10:51,920 --> 00:10:55,800
Jiang’s former school. Jiang went to give a speech 
in front of these protesters, which turned into  

155
00:10:55,800 --> 00:11:00,480
a three hour long shouting match, culminating in 
Jiang reciting the Gettysburg Address, in English,  

156
00:11:00,480 --> 00:11:05,160
to the students. It was just a kind of confusing 
ordeal, with neither side really understanding  

157
00:11:05,160 --> 00:11:08,520
what exactly happened, if anything.
He had a few private meetings with student  

158
00:11:08,520 --> 00:11:12,600
leaders, none of which led to anything. Jiang 
refused to acquiesce to any of their demands,  

159
00:11:12,600 --> 00:11:16,160
and later deployed unarmed police to break 
up the protests when they attempted to block  

160
00:11:16,160 --> 00:11:20,840
major roads. This backfired, and thousands 
more were in the streets within a few days,  

161
00:11:20,840 --> 00:11:25,080
prompting Jiang to ask for help and advice from 
Beijing. He was advised to meet with them again,  

162
00:11:25,080 --> 00:11:29,680
but this, yet again, went nowhere.
Factory workers also began joining the protests,  

163
00:11:29,680 --> 00:11:33,680
prompting much attention to be given to the 
situation by Beijing. Incredibly luckily for  

164
00:11:33,680 --> 00:11:38,080
Jiang, the protests died out after a few days, 
with no strong action needing to be taken. It’s  

165
00:11:38,080 --> 00:11:41,960
debated why this happened, but Jiang’s sympathy 
towards student movements and his genuine desire  

166
00:11:41,960 --> 00:11:46,240
for reform, albeit more limited than the students’ 
demands, helped assuage their concerns.
 

167
00:11:46,240 --> 00:11:50,160
In Beijing at the same time, top leaders were 
making a decision that would totally never come  

168
00:11:50,160 --> 00:11:54,640
back to bite them. Deng Xiaoping and Zhao Ziyang 
were in the process of removing Hu Yaobang from  

169
00:11:54,640 --> 00:11:58,880
power, for going too far with his political 
reforms. These reforms had led to an easing of  

170
00:11:58,880 --> 00:12:03,280
tensions, and the dispersal of most protests. 
Surely this will have no consequences.
 

171
00:12:03,280 --> 00:12:06,800
Jiang had impressed top leaders with his 
relatively middle-of-the-road approach,  

172
00:12:06,800 --> 00:12:11,240
not angering any particular group. Jiang made sure 
to quickly fall in line with the new party line,  

173
00:12:11,240 --> 00:12:15,640
that being railing against the “bourgeois 
liberalism” of Hu Yaobang. He reinforced  

174
00:12:15,640 --> 00:12:19,960
this general position with an interview with the 
Los Angeles Times in 1987, where he argued that  

175
00:12:19,960 --> 00:12:24,120
putting down the protests was needed to allow for 
Shanghai’s greater opening up to the world.
 

176
00:12:24,120 --> 00:12:28,880
And open up, Shanghai sure did. Jiang got approval 
to formally transition Shanghai to a market  

177
00:12:28,880 --> 00:12:33,600
economy, and did away with many regulations in the 
city. He also hired many competent subordinates to  

178
00:12:33,600 --> 00:12:37,400
handle the day-to-day economics and management of 
the city, so he could focus more on the government  

179
00:12:37,400 --> 00:12:41,360
and political side of things. This gave him 
the opportunity to frequently meet with the  

180
00:12:41,360 --> 00:12:45,440
many foreign visitors to Shanghai, which was now 
a common stop on foreign tours of China, and gave  

181
00:12:45,440 --> 00:12:49,400
him some positive attention internationally. 
He also now had a free hand to talk about  

182
00:12:49,400 --> 00:12:53,720
some political reforms, though very minor and 
vague, mainly giving speeches about how “taboo  

183
00:12:53,720 --> 00:12:58,320
opinions” should be allowed to be voiced.
The catalyst for national reforms, Hu Yaobang,  

184
00:12:58,320 --> 00:13:03,280
died in 1989. Jiang was actually in attendance at 
the meeting where Hu had the first of a series of  

185
00:13:03,280 --> 00:13:07,920
heart attacks that would kill him in April of that 
year. Hu Yaobang was the only major politician  

186
00:13:07,920 --> 00:13:12,600
talking about serious political reforms, and the 
opening of intellectual spaces. Gatherings and  

187
00:13:12,600 --> 00:13:17,240
memorials for Hu quickly turned into protests in 
Beijing, which became huge protests in Shanghai  

188
00:13:17,240 --> 00:13:21,280
when word spread there. Many people were 
outraged by how he was removed from power  

189
00:13:21,280 --> 00:13:25,920
and the attempted censorship of his ideas.
The protests in Shanghai weren’t as big of a deal  

190
00:13:25,920 --> 00:13:30,360
as what a certain newspaper was printing, that 
being the World Economic Herald. Considered the  

191
00:13:30,360 --> 00:13:34,600
most reformist media outlet in the country, they 
were now openly publishing articles supporting  

192
00:13:34,600 --> 00:13:39,600
Hu and slamming top leaders for ousting him from 
power. Jiang’s initial response was to demand the  

193
00:13:39,600 --> 00:13:44,120
paper vet all new articles with party censors 
in Shanghai. The editor of the paper refused,  

194
00:13:44,120 --> 00:13:47,880
uncensored versions of the paper were printed, 
and the editor was nowhere to be found.
 

195
00:13:47,880 --> 00:13:52,240
The local party apparatus quickly made the paper 
be subservient to a five-person review board,  

196
00:13:52,240 --> 00:13:56,120
and Jiang fired the editor. This, considering 
what the response to these protests would  

197
00:13:56,120 --> 00:14:00,800
famously culminate in, seems relatively minor 
and restrained. Zhao Ziyang, now the second most  

198
00:14:00,800 --> 00:14:05,160
important person in the country, didn’t think 
so, and was furious. Zhao had a reputation as  

199
00:14:05,160 --> 00:14:08,960
a reformer, and the World Economic Herald 
was one of his biggest sources of support,  

200
00:14:08,960 --> 00:14:13,160
now essentially decapitated. Zhao criticized 
Jiang for his hasty decision, calling his  

201
00:14:13,160 --> 00:14:17,680
solution simplistic. Jiang also had pressure from 
the hardliners in the party, since his review  

202
00:14:17,680 --> 00:14:21,520
board wasn’t doing their jobs, and were still 
letting anti-government articles through.
 

203
00:14:21,520 --> 00:14:25,680
This turned into a weeks-long battle, mostly Zhao 
and Jiang sending angry letters to each other,  

204
00:14:25,680 --> 00:14:29,800
with Zhao on the attack and Jiang playing 
defense. Things weren’t helped by Gorbachev’s  

205
00:14:29,800 --> 00:14:34,200
visit to China, in which Shanghai would be a stop. 
Jiang was barely able to rally enough police to  

206
00:14:34,200 --> 00:14:39,040
clear Gorby’s route of the estimated 100,000 
protesters now in Shanghai. A few days later,  

207
00:14:39,040 --> 00:14:42,560
Jiang was finally able to talk down most of 
the protesters, walking into the crowd with a  

208
00:14:42,560 --> 00:14:46,840
megaphone, promising to hold talks and supporting 
the anti-corruption side of their protest.
 

209
00:14:46,840 --> 00:14:51,000
Back in Beijing, Zhao Ziyang tried a similar 
tactic, walking into Tiananmen and basically  

210
00:14:51,000 --> 00:14:54,840
saying “we’re really sorry about all this, can 
you all just go home?” When this didn’t work,  

211
00:14:54,840 --> 00:14:59,080
top leaders came back with a different plan: 
martial law. Surely, this would never come  

212
00:14:59,080 --> 00:15:03,160
back to bite them. Soldiers tried to clear 
Beijing of protesters over several days,  

213
00:15:03,160 --> 00:15:07,240
but were largely unsuccessful, and only served 
to turn a few protesters to violence.
 

214
00:15:07,240 --> 00:15:11,160
Zhao became the protesters’ newest target, 
and there were calls for him to step down.  

215
00:15:11,160 --> 00:15:15,080
Deng Xiaoping’s patience with his continued 
bungling of the protests was wearing thin,  

216
00:15:15,080 --> 00:15:19,640
and he began exploring options for a replacement 
as general secretary. Deng convened a secret  

217
00:15:19,640 --> 00:15:23,880
meeting with a few top officials on May 27th, 
where Jiang Zemin was selected to be the new  

218
00:15:23,880 --> 00:15:28,480
general secretary, after a few hours of debate. 
The decision came down to his relative youth,  

219
00:15:28,480 --> 00:15:32,440
success with economic reforms, and being a fairly 
personable guy who could help with the protests  

220
00:15:32,440 --> 00:15:37,040
and similar discontent in the future. Most 
people were shocked and surprised by this choice,  

221
00:15:37,040 --> 00:15:40,480
as was Jiang, who had no idea he was 
even up for consideration until a private  

222
00:15:40,480 --> 00:15:43,840
meeting with Deng a few days later.
He got acquainted with his new position for a  

223
00:15:43,840 --> 00:15:48,560
few days, and boy, what days those were. These 
were the final days of the Beijing protests,  

224
00:15:48,560 --> 00:15:52,520
culminating in the Tiananmen Square Massacre. 
Jiang’s role in the events of these days are  

225
00:15:52,520 --> 00:15:56,840
hard to say, we pretty much only have anecdotal 
accounts. Some say he had no involvement, some  

226
00:15:56,840 --> 00:16:01,320
say he was deeply involved. What we do know is he 
was generally against the heavy-handed response,  

227
00:16:01,320 --> 00:16:05,320
and pushed for police reform, preferring them to 
use non-lethal means for crowd control.
 

228
00:16:05,320 --> 00:16:09,560
Jiang was officially elected as 
general secretary on June 28th, 1989,  

229
00:16:09,560 --> 00:16:14,440
around the same time Deng Xiaoping retired from 
politics, formally turning over the keys. People  

230
00:16:14,440 --> 00:16:18,720
in China and internationally were surprised by 
this selection, he was a periphery politician  

231
00:16:18,720 --> 00:16:22,720
at best, a liability at worst. Basically 
nobody thought his term would last long,  

232
00:16:22,720 --> 00:16:26,720
one diplomat in Beijing said he would be running 
a transitional government at best. Though,  

233
00:16:26,720 --> 00:16:31,040
many were hopeful. He was untainted by many of 
the scandals and issues of Beijing politics,  

234
00:16:31,040 --> 00:16:34,320
and had shown his willingness to work with 
foreign countries throughout his career.
 

235
00:16:34,320 --> 00:16:38,640
Jiang immediately got to work on addressing a few 
basic concerns of the protesters, mainly on the  

236
00:16:38,640 --> 00:16:42,480
corruption front. He tightened regulations 
on government officials, no more banquets,  

237
00:16:42,480 --> 00:16:47,040
foreign cars, or big year-end bonuses. He also 
handled the response to foreign media about the  

238
00:16:47,040 --> 00:16:51,120
Tiananmen incident, in a major press conference 
where any question was permitted. He asserted that  

239
00:16:51,120 --> 00:16:55,080
the soldiers only opened fire after they had 
been attacked by protesters. He stressed that  

240
00:16:55,080 --> 00:16:59,200
this was a one-off incident, and that it shouldn’t 
dissuade foreign investment and interest in China.  

241
00:16:59,200 --> 00:17:01,800
Overall, foreign media was very 
impressed with his demeanor,  

242
00:17:01,800 --> 00:17:05,320
a Chinese leader taking questions from the 
press this openly was unheard of.
 

243
00:17:05,320 --> 00:17:10,200
He spent the rest of 1989 and 1990 bolstering 
domestic support, mainly making public visits  

244
00:17:10,200 --> 00:17:14,880
to various mines, factories and farms. He 
visited Kim Il-Sung in North Korea, assuring  

245
00:17:14,880 --> 00:17:18,400
each other they would work together to fend off 
the collapse of communism happening in Europe,  

246
00:17:18,400 --> 00:17:23,520
from spreading to Asia. Invited a few university 
students to Zhongnanhai, that’s nice. All in all,  

247
00:17:23,520 --> 00:17:27,120
pretty typical stuff for a new leader to 
do. He still didn’t really have a base,  

248
00:17:27,120 --> 00:17:30,920
and was very dependent on the support and advice 
of Deng Xiaoping in these first years.
 

249
00:17:30,920 --> 00:17:36,720
1992 saw one of Deng’s last major political moves, 
his famous “Southern Tour.” Economic reforms had  

250
00:17:36,720 --> 00:17:40,200
been curtailed by conservative elements in 
the government in the aftermath of Tiananmen,  

251
00:17:40,200 --> 00:17:44,160
and foreign investors were scared off from 
China by the incident. Guangdong and Shenzhen  

252
00:17:44,160 --> 00:17:47,600
in the south were still progressing with the 
reforms, and were the fastest growing regions  

253
00:17:47,600 --> 00:17:51,520
in China as a result. Deng visited these 
areas, and praised them for their progress,  

254
00:17:51,520 --> 00:17:55,280
and spoke against those still against free 
market reform. While Jiang wasn’t really a  

255
00:17:55,280 --> 00:17:59,880
focus of anything he said, Jiang still interpreted 
many of his comments as criticizing him, and moved  

256
00:17:59,880 --> 00:18:04,120
more towards reform as a result.
1992 was mostly Jiang securing his position,  

257
00:18:04,120 --> 00:18:08,480
or more accurately, Deng securing it for 
him. Deng got the military to fall in line,  

258
00:18:08,480 --> 00:18:12,680
and replaced many of the most conservative 
politicians with younger reform-minded ones.  

259
00:18:12,680 --> 00:18:16,760
Deng made a twenty minute long speech in front of 
the National People’s Congress supporting Jiang,  

260
00:18:16,760 --> 00:18:20,880
crushing any doubt of him as Deng’s formal 
successor. Jiang made a couple international  

261
00:18:20,880 --> 00:18:25,080
trips, one to Japan and one to South Korea, 
after finally establishing diplomatic relations  

262
00:18:25,080 --> 00:18:29,440
with the latter. This made Kim Il-Sung mad 
and his request for military material aid  

263
00:18:29,440 --> 00:18:33,680
was rebuffed by Jiang that same year.
Funny anecdote from this time, Jiang really  

264
00:18:33,680 --> 00:18:38,120
liked to receive reports and talk directly 
with those who reported to him. Dr. Song Jian,  

265
00:18:38,120 --> 00:18:41,240
a scientist and mathematician who 
worked in China’s aerospace industry,  

266
00:18:41,240 --> 00:18:45,560
was requested to just… give him any articles 
or papers he found interesting. He’d just walk  

267
00:18:45,560 --> 00:18:50,240
into Jiang’s office and hand him some scientific 
documents every once in a while. Incredibly funny,  

268
00:18:50,240 --> 00:18:54,520
this is how I’d run a government.
By 1993, Jiang was very secure in his position,  

269
00:18:54,520 --> 00:18:59,040
and was fairly popular as a leader. He began 
fulfilling some of his promises he made earlier,  

270
00:18:59,040 --> 00:19:02,960
like police reform. The People’s Armed Police, 
which were essentially cops with military  

271
00:19:02,960 --> 00:19:07,200
gear before, were given proper riot control 
equipment. He also transferred many units from  

272
00:19:07,200 --> 00:19:12,400
military authority to civilian police authority. 
Don’t think he was some ACAB crusader, though.  

273
00:19:12,400 --> 00:19:16,320
He also expanded the powers of the Ministry 
of State Security, China’s intelligence and  

274
00:19:16,320 --> 00:19:21,200
secret police agency. He allowed the MSS to spy 
on basically anyone they wanted without a warrant,  

275
00:19:21,200 --> 00:19:25,360
and had them report directly to him.
Inflation and rising costs were a big problem  

276
00:19:25,360 --> 00:19:29,520
at this time. China’s economy was growing by 
twelve percent each year, by far the highest  

277
00:19:29,520 --> 00:19:33,960
in the world. Costs however, were increasing by 
about forty percent each year for most goods and  

278
00:19:33,960 --> 00:19:37,760
services. This was mainly curtailed by reducing 
the amount of loans given out by the People’s  

279
00:19:37,760 --> 00:19:42,240
Bank of China, which slowed overall growth, 
but prevented a huge inflation crisis.
 

280
00:19:42,240 --> 00:19:46,680
1993 had quite a lot of diplomatic activity, 
with some back channel talks between Jiang and  

281
00:19:46,680 --> 00:19:51,160
the president of Taiwan via the US ambassador 
to China. He tried to get Beijing to host the  

282
00:19:51,160 --> 00:19:55,680
2000 Olympics, didn’t work. Placated Britain 
about Hong Kong, who were suddenly freaking out  

283
00:19:55,680 --> 00:20:00,080
about there being a new leader in Beijing. Got 
a container ship seized by the US for allegedly  

284
00:20:00,080 --> 00:20:04,360
carrying chemical weapons, though none were ever 
found. I’m sure America will be careful about  

285
00:20:04,360 --> 00:20:09,320
making accusations like that in the future.
1994 was marked with continued austerity measures,  

286
00:20:09,320 --> 00:20:13,120
now increasingly unpopular. Some conservatives 
in the government argued with Jiang that he  

287
00:20:13,120 --> 00:20:16,960
should enforce Mao-style price controls 
to fix the immediate issue. While Jiang  

288
00:20:16,960 --> 00:20:20,360
was deeply bothered by the continuing inflation 
problem, he trusted Deng, and knew allowing the  

289
00:20:20,360 --> 00:20:24,680
free market to continue, even if it had some 
short term growing pains, would be beneficial  

290
00:20:24,680 --> 00:20:27,800
for the country overall.
He continued many of the military  

291
00:20:27,800 --> 00:20:32,520
reforms Deng started in the ‘80s, and made a ton 
of visits to military academies and installations.  

292
00:20:32,520 --> 00:20:36,280
Overall, he had a fairly hands off approach to 
the military, as the first leader of the People’s  

293
00:20:36,280 --> 00:20:40,840
Republic without any military experience.
China-US relations deteriorated quite a bit,  

294
00:20:40,840 --> 00:20:45,120
with Jiang and Clinton exchanging heated remarks 
about each other’s governments. Clinton demanded  

295
00:20:45,120 --> 00:20:49,120
China improve their human rights situation, 
and Jiang accused America of trying to make  

296
00:20:49,120 --> 00:20:53,360
China into a vassal. Things weren’t going well 
with Britain either, as he tried to hastily  

297
00:20:53,360 --> 00:20:58,600
renegotiate the exact terms for the return of Hong 
Kong to China, scheduled to happen in 1997, and  

298
00:20:58,600 --> 00:21:02,440
was very angry when the British rebuffed him. He 
did formally get the ball rolling on joining the  

299
00:21:02,440 --> 00:21:07,840
World Trade Organization this year, too.
1995 saw greater economic policy centralization,  

300
00:21:07,840 --> 00:21:11,680
not to be confused with a return to a planned 
economy. It was common at this time for the  

301
00:21:11,680 --> 00:21:15,520
government to draft a new policy, and receive 
unanimous support from provincial governors,  

302
00:21:15,520 --> 00:21:19,480
but with various explanations about how 
their particular province should be exempt.  

303
00:21:19,480 --> 00:21:23,960
He personally met with every provincial governor, 
and made them pledge to follow Beijing’s policies,  

304
00:21:23,960 --> 00:21:27,120
whatever they may be, with threats 
of dismissal if they refused.
 

305
00:21:27,120 --> 00:21:30,640
He also began taking greater control of the 
media, prohibiting foreign investment in  

306
00:21:30,640 --> 00:21:34,200
Chinese media organizations, and forbidding 
Chinese reporters from writing for foreign  

307
00:21:34,200 --> 00:21:38,880
organizations. Media were also prohibited 
from reporting on “negative phenomena,” such  

308
00:21:38,880 --> 00:21:42,520
as protests or legal disputes.
He gave a speech on Taiwan that would  

309
00:21:42,520 --> 00:21:46,560
set the tone for policy regarding that dispute 
for a while. Jiang softened the tone on Taiwan  

310
00:21:46,560 --> 00:21:49,440
quite a bit, saying they would be allowed 
to retain their own government, military,  

311
00:21:49,440 --> 00:21:54,080
and independent legal system in a hypothetical 
reunification. This speech made nobody happy,  

312
00:21:54,080 --> 00:21:58,720
he threw in a vague military threat at the end, 
which made Taiwan nervous. The military and rest  

313
00:21:58,720 --> 00:22:02,440
of the government wasn’t happy about Taiwan 
being given all these concessions.
 

314
00:22:02,440 --> 00:22:06,560
Dr. Song Jian, his scientist friend, also 
formally made a proposal to the government  

315
00:22:06,560 --> 00:22:10,440
this year for a program to advance science 
and education in the country. Jiang got this  

316
00:22:10,440 --> 00:22:14,440
proposal pushed through the Politburo, and 
pledged to end China’s exam-based educational  

317
00:22:14,440 --> 00:22:18,960
system. Yeah, that really worked out.
China-US relations only got worse, when the  

318
00:22:18,960 --> 00:22:23,640
president of Taiwan visited America. Clinton had 
allegedly promised Jiang at a meeting in Moscow  

319
00:22:23,640 --> 00:22:27,600
that the president wouldn’t be allowed in, but 
the trip was approved anyway. Jiang felt betrayed,  

320
00:22:27,600 --> 00:22:31,840
and vocally condemned the US for this. Jiang 
stated privately to military leaders that “the  

321
00:22:31,840 --> 00:22:36,160
Taiwan independence movement is getting out of 
hand,” and to increase military readiness.
 

322
00:22:36,160 --> 00:22:41,160
This would lead to the Third Taiwan Strait 
Crisis, continuing into 1996. Tons of missile  

323
00:22:41,160 --> 00:22:45,680
tests and naval exercises surrounded the island 
for months, leading to a fairly major economic  

324
00:22:45,680 --> 00:22:50,960
downturn for Taiwan. Shipping costs exploded and 
the stock market crashed. It eventually died down,  

325
00:22:50,960 --> 00:22:54,600
with China generally considered to have “won” 
the incident, coming out looking stronger than  

326
00:22:54,600 --> 00:22:58,120
they entered. Though, it did allow that 
Taiwanese president to win a comfortable  

327
00:22:58,120 --> 00:23:02,320
election victory during the crisis.
He made a visit to the UN General Assembly,  

328
00:23:02,320 --> 00:23:06,400
making a speech speaking against “big powers” 
who use the pretext of “human rights” to  

329
00:23:06,400 --> 00:23:09,920
interfere with other countries. He met with 
Clinton on the sidelines, and the two of them  

330
00:23:09,920 --> 00:23:14,560
talked for a bit and largely made up.
1996 saw some interesting messaging from Jiang.  

331
00:23:14,560 --> 00:23:19,080
He gave speeches telling officials to “focus 
on politics” and “increase cultural and moral  

332
00:23:19,080 --> 00:23:23,680
fortitude.” Jiang spoke about how China’s 
cultural, spiritual, and moral aspects  

333
00:23:23,680 --> 00:23:28,000
were falling behind its economic and material 
development. This was a strange turn to say the  

334
00:23:28,000 --> 00:23:32,640
least, and worried many people. Talk like this was 
last heard during the Cultural Revolution.
 

335
00:23:32,640 --> 00:23:35,880
The ideas he put forth, what would be 
known as “Jiang Thought,” encompassed a  

336
00:23:35,880 --> 00:23:39,200
broad integration of the new free market 
thinking and system with the old Marxist  

337
00:23:39,200 --> 00:23:43,560
ideas of the country. More broadly, it was 
pushing back against Western culture that was  

338
00:23:43,560 --> 00:23:48,040
increasingly intruding into China. This was just 
against the cultural side of Western influence,  

339
00:23:48,040 --> 00:23:52,280
Western money and expertise was still more than 
welcome. An article in the People’s Daily put  

340
00:23:52,280 --> 00:23:56,480
it as “China shouldn’t give up eating for 
fear of choking.” Ultimately, this wasn’t  

341
00:23:56,480 --> 00:24:01,240
turned into concrete policy, and was just a vague 
directive to improve morality and thinking.
 

342
00:24:01,240 --> 00:24:06,120
He visited a ton of countries in 1996, mainly 
in Africa, Central Asia, and Europe. Perhaps  

343
00:24:06,120 --> 00:24:10,040
the most famous images from these trips were 
him very obviously combing his hair in front of  

344
00:24:10,040 --> 00:24:14,640
the king of Spain. He did a brief tour around 
Asia, became the first modern Chinese leader  

345
00:24:14,640 --> 00:24:18,640
to visit India and sang Elvis Presley songs 
with the president of the Philippines.
 

346
00:24:18,640 --> 00:24:22,400
The two most important events of 1997 
had be to the death of Deng Xiaoping,  

347
00:24:22,400 --> 00:24:26,680
and the return of Hong Kong to China. Deng 
Xiaoping’s death was pretty inconsequential,  

348
00:24:26,680 --> 00:24:30,200
his health had been declining for a few years, 
and everything was prepared well in advance.  

349
00:24:30,200 --> 00:24:33,480
Jiang gave a fifty minute long speech at 
his funeral, and took the opportunity to  

350
00:24:33,480 --> 00:24:38,800
reinforce his political position. Recordings 
of Deng praising Jiang were rebroadcast on TV,  

351
00:24:38,800 --> 00:24:43,400
a soundbite of Deng saying “the choice of Jiang 
Zemin is correct” was frequently repeated.
 

352
00:24:43,400 --> 00:24:46,760
For Hong Kong, the handover was also very 
smooth and rehearsed, but not without some  

353
00:24:46,760 --> 00:24:50,680
minor controversies. The head of the Hong Kong 
government, the position of governor, would be  

354
00:24:50,680 --> 00:24:55,240
replaced by the position of Chief Executive. 
The first Chief Executive, Tung Chee-hwa,  

355
00:24:55,240 --> 00:24:59,800
had been chosen by a 400 person committee, rather 
than a direct election in Hong Kong as many were  

356
00:24:59,800 --> 00:25:04,560
expecting. Prime Minister Tony Blair boycotted 
the handover ceremony as a result.
 

357
00:25:04,560 --> 00:25:09,600
1997 also saw Jiang’s first formal summit with the 
United States. This was a very extensive visit,  

358
00:25:09,600 --> 00:25:13,280
going all over the country. Protests by 
various activist groups, human rights,  

359
00:25:13,280 --> 00:25:17,200
Tibetan, and Taiwanese especially, were planning 
gatherings at every stop along the way.
 

360
00:25:17,200 --> 00:25:21,320
The trip was overall a success, with Jiang 
and Clinton making firm progress on a variety  

361
00:25:21,320 --> 00:25:25,440
of issues. The two finally got along at a more 
personal level, with Jiang referring to Clinton  

362
00:25:25,440 --> 00:25:30,040
as “my friend Bill Clinton” from now on. He took 
a few news interviews, and answered plenty of  

363
00:25:30,040 --> 00:25:35,200
unscripted questions at press conferences.
1998 was a fairly eventful year, some of the  

364
00:25:35,200 --> 00:25:38,680
most notable events were an increase in 
foreign movies being allowed into China,  

365
00:25:38,680 --> 00:25:42,680
after the success of Titanic, a visit from 
Bill Clinton, and the elevation of Hu Jintao,  

366
00:25:42,680 --> 00:25:47,320
who would succeed Jiang as leader eventually. 
India and Pakistan exchanged nuclear tests,  

367
00:25:47,320 --> 00:25:51,280
increasing tension for a while in Asia. One of 
India’s cited reasons for their test was the  

368
00:25:51,280 --> 00:25:55,480
threat posed by China, which Jiang was apparently 
legitimately surprised and confused by.
 

369
00:25:55,480 --> 00:25:59,400
Some interesting military reforms happened 
this year, regarding the military’s influence  

370
00:25:59,400 --> 00:26:03,320
in business. Due to budget cuts in the 
‘80s, some parts of the military became  

371
00:26:03,320 --> 00:26:07,280
involved both legitimate and illegitimate 
business, with surprisingly far reach. The  

372
00:26:07,280 --> 00:26:12,080
PLA was operating everything from hotels 
to nightclubs to airlines to cell networks  

373
00:26:12,080 --> 00:26:16,200
to professional basketball teams. They also 
participated in smuggling and bootlegging,  

374
00:26:16,200 --> 00:26:20,240
particularly movies and software.
Jiang had quite a bit of sway with the military  

375
00:26:20,240 --> 00:26:25,000
now, and decreed that all such enterprises should 
be immediately broken up and dissolved. Top brass  

376
00:26:25,000 --> 00:26:28,840
complied, but there were many grumblings from 
less senior officers. He further stretched  

377
00:26:28,840 --> 00:26:32,360
his political capital with the military when 
he required their assistance in dealing with  

378
00:26:32,360 --> 00:26:35,720
major flooding in the country, that displaced 
more than a quarter billion people.
 

379
00:26:35,720 --> 00:26:39,800
Things were generally fine with both of these, 
though there were some minor protests in 1999  

380
00:26:39,800 --> 00:26:44,280
by workers who lost their jobs when their PLA 
employers had to shutter their businesses. These  

381
00:26:44,280 --> 00:26:49,600
were hardly the protests of concern, however. On 
April 25th, over 10,000 members of a cult known as  

382
00:26:49,600 --> 00:26:54,960
Falun Gong began encircling Zhongnanhai. With an 
estimated two million members, not much in terms  

383
00:26:54,960 --> 00:26:59,040
of China’s vast population, many top leaders had 
never even heard of the people surrounding the  

384
00:26:59,040 --> 00:27:03,000
main government building in Beijing. This 
protest was over some Falun Gong members  

385
00:27:03,000 --> 00:27:06,600
who had been arrested for protesting in front 
of a newspaper office that printed an article  

386
00:27:06,600 --> 00:27:11,400
they believed was defamatory to their sect.
The protest was dispersed fairly easily, after a  

387
00:27:11,400 --> 00:27:15,200
spokesman was sent out to speak with them. He said 
the government had no dispute with them, but that  

388
00:27:15,200 --> 00:27:19,440
they couldn’t engage in this type of behavior. The 
protesters very quickly left after this.
 

389
00:27:19,440 --> 00:27:23,720
Jiang was enraged by this incident. It had 
come completely out of nowhere, and worse yet,  

390
00:27:23,720 --> 00:27:28,160
it was revealed there were party members among 
the protesters. Jiang also had a more personal  

391
00:27:28,160 --> 00:27:31,840
grievance with the cult. A friend of his had 
joined for the meditation and exercise part of  

392
00:27:31,840 --> 00:27:35,840
their beliefs, but died from a brain hemorrhage 
after she refused medical care due to the cult’s  

393
00:27:35,840 --> 00:27:39,800
prohibition against modern medicine.
His response to Falun Gong would have to wait,  

394
00:27:39,800 --> 00:27:43,920
as a much more important event in May captured 
national attention: the NATO bombing of the  

395
00:27:43,920 --> 00:27:49,240
Chinese embassy in Serbia. This was during the 
broader NATO air campaign against Serbia, where an  

396
00:27:49,240 --> 00:27:54,080
American B-2 Spirit dropped bombs on the Chinese 
embassy, killing three people and injuring dozens  

397
00:27:54,080 --> 00:27:59,320
more. The incident is still pretty confusing, to 
say the least. The CIA, who organized the attack,  

398
00:27:59,320 --> 00:28:03,600
claimed it was a mere mistake, which seems hard 
to believe, given the precision bombs used. On  

399
00:28:03,600 --> 00:28:07,200
the other hand, there’s not really a benefit 
to attacking a random Chinese embassy.
 

400
00:28:07,200 --> 00:28:11,280
Jiang did get a lick in on Falun Gong with 
it, joking that “if Falun Gong masters can  

401
00:28:11,280 --> 00:28:15,520
predict the future, why couldn’t they predict 
the attack on our embassy?” Huge anti-American  

402
00:28:15,520 --> 00:28:19,640
protests broke out around China, snarling 
many of Jiang’s reforms. His opening up to  

403
00:28:19,640 --> 00:28:22,920
the West now seemed much less appealing 
to many people, and his bid to join the  

404
00:28:22,920 --> 00:28:27,360
World Trade Organization was put on hold.
Rocks were thrown at the US embassy in Beijing,  

405
00:28:27,360 --> 00:28:31,280
and consulates were surrounded. Very strong 
statements against America and NATO were  

406
00:28:31,280 --> 00:28:34,920
put out by various government organs. The 
protests wore on for about a week, before  

407
00:28:34,920 --> 00:28:39,080
the government finally intervened to halt them. 
Jiang finally accepted a phone call from Clinton,  

408
00:28:39,080 --> 00:28:42,880
after declining them for the entire week.
Attention of the government quickly turned back to  

409
00:28:42,880 --> 00:28:47,320
Falun Gong, who had restrictions placed on them, 
and in practice it was a total ban. It was now  

410
00:28:47,320 --> 00:28:51,960
illegal to have gatherings, spread cult materials, 
or to demonstrate for the cult. An arrest warrant  

411
00:28:51,960 --> 00:28:56,680
was also put out for Li Hongzhi, the leader of the 
cult, who had left the country prior. Falun Gong’s  

412
00:28:56,680 --> 00:29:01,000
response was to claim they had been responsible 
for the NATO bombing of the Chinese embassy, using  

413
00:29:01,000 --> 00:29:06,440
their leader’s supposed supernatural abilities. 
I’m not kidding. But, for now, the ban elicited  

414
00:29:06,440 --> 00:29:09,920
some critical comments about the government, 
but it didn’t have too many consequences.
 

415
00:29:09,920 --> 00:29:14,320
2000 had some big policy changes, including 
the implementation of Jiang Zemin’s “Three  

416
00:29:14,320 --> 00:29:18,680
Represents” theory. This was essentially 
a plan to “modernize Marxism.” The three  

417
00:29:18,680 --> 00:29:23,360
things to “represent” with this policy are 
advanced productive forces, advanced culture,  

418
00:29:23,360 --> 00:29:27,160
and the interests of the Chinese people. This 
whole thing sounds kind of strange in English,  

419
00:29:27,160 --> 00:29:31,080
I mean, even the name sounds like something from 
a bad sci-fi book, but it makes more sense in  

420
00:29:31,080 --> 00:29:35,480
Chinese. The long and short of it was an attempt 
to update China’s Marxist rhetoric and culture  

421
00:29:35,480 --> 00:29:39,240
to incorporate the new economic realities 
and wealth now sweeping the nation.
 

422
00:29:39,240 --> 00:29:43,240
He focused again on education reform in 
2000, setting a goal of China being one  

423
00:29:43,240 --> 00:29:47,280
of the top ten countries in science by 
2010. Jiang even got to write a couple  

424
00:29:47,280 --> 00:29:51,280
pieces for the journal Science, an honor not 
usually afforded to national leaders.
 

425
00:29:51,280 --> 00:29:55,040
2000 saw two of his most famous moments 
on camera, the first being an interview  

426
00:29:55,040 --> 00:29:58,960
with Mike Wallace of 60 Minutes. It’s quite the 
interview, it’s on YouTube if you want to watch  

427
00:29:58,960 --> 00:30:03,120
it. Wallace didn’t hold back with his questions, 
and Jiang fired back with some tough questions of  

428
00:30:03,120 --> 00:30:07,040
his own. The interview left many in America with 
a good impression of Jiang, even if the editing  

429
00:30:07,040 --> 00:30:11,360
and translation choices for some of his comments 
were a little inaccurate, to say the least.
 

430
00:30:15,240 --> 00:30:19,560
The other media incident happened a few weeks 
later, at a press conference in Beijing. Jiang  

431
00:30:19,560 --> 00:30:23,712
blew up at some reporters from Hong Kong after 
one asked if his endorsement of Tung Chee-hwa’s  

432
00:30:23,712 --> 00:30:29,000
reelection campaign was an “imperial appointment.” 
The result was… I’ll just let you watch for  

433
00:30:29,000 --> 00:30:56,240
yourself. If you’ve seen any video of Jiang Zemin, 
this is probably the clip you’ve seen.
 

434
00:31:15,000 --> 00:31:17,880
Absolutely amazing.
Ultimately, these two events  

435
00:31:17,880 --> 00:31:22,200
didn’t really matter much, but Jiang got a couple 
vague criticisms from Politburo members about how  

436
00:31:22,200 --> 00:31:27,200
politicians should “show decorum.”
2001 was a low point in US-China relations,  

437
00:31:27,200 --> 00:31:31,920
with a change in leadership in America, and 
the Hainan Island incident. The US flew,  

438
00:31:31,920 --> 00:31:36,200
and still flies, reconnaissance flights in 
international waters, but near the Chinese coast,  

439
00:31:36,200 --> 00:31:40,560
quite frequently. China typically responds with 
fighters to intercept the plane, keeping a safe  

440
00:31:40,560 --> 00:31:44,760
distance. It’s this weird sort of diplomatic 
dance, but it’s a pretty common phenomenon.
 

441
00:31:44,760 --> 00:31:49,760
On April 1st, 2001, a US Navy EP-3 signal 
intelligence plane was conducting one of  

442
00:31:49,760 --> 00:31:54,360
these patrols near the island of Hainan. Two 
Chinese J-8 fighters were sent to intercept  

443
00:31:54,360 --> 00:31:58,520
and monitor the American aircraft. It still 
isn’t clear what exactly happened, but one  

444
00:31:58,520 --> 00:32:02,400
of the fighters and the American plane collided 
with each other, crashing the fighter into the  

445
00:32:02,400 --> 00:32:06,520
sea and the death of its pilot, and forcing 
the American plane to land on Hainan.
 

446
00:32:06,520 --> 00:32:11,040
The new American president, George W. Bush, 
demanded China not tamper with or board the  

447
00:32:11,040 --> 00:32:15,640
downed plane, claiming it had sovereign immunity. 
That worked about as well as those sovereign  

448
00:32:15,640 --> 00:32:20,720
citizen license plates. Jiang blamed the US for 
the incident, and demanded an official apology.  

449
00:32:20,720 --> 00:32:25,280
He also ordered a huge search and rescue operation 
for the downed pilot, to no avail, sadly.
 

450
00:32:25,280 --> 00:32:28,960
The US was reluctant to issue an apology, 
seeing their plane as having done nothing  

451
00:32:28,960 --> 00:32:33,160
more than make an emergency landing. China 
allowed American diplomats to visit the crew  

452
00:32:33,160 --> 00:32:37,000
of the plane, confirming their wellbeing. 
The crew was held in China for ten days,  

453
00:32:37,000 --> 00:32:40,920
when they were freed by an official apology 
from the State Department for the incident. The  

454
00:32:40,920 --> 00:32:45,000
plane was eventually returned to the US as well, 
though after it had been completely disassembled  

455
00:32:45,000 --> 00:32:49,000
and analyzed by Chinese engineers.
In happier news, Beijing won its bid to  

456
00:32:49,000 --> 00:32:52,880
host the 2008 Olympics in July of that 
year. In good news for people who like  

457
00:32:52,880 --> 00:32:57,440
cheap products but bad news for anyone outside of 
China with a manufacturing job, China also joined  

458
00:32:57,440 --> 00:33:01,400
the World Trade Organization that year.
Jiang and Bush didn’t get along for the first  

459
00:33:01,400 --> 00:33:06,120
few months of his term, but they reconciled after 
Jiang supported America after 9/11. They held a  

460
00:33:06,120 --> 00:33:10,120
summit in Shanghai, where Jiang firmly threw 
China’s support behind the US anti-terrorism  

461
00:33:10,120 --> 00:33:14,480
effort. This was partially to get a free hand to 
combat terrorism within China, particularly in  

462
00:33:14,480 --> 00:33:19,040
Xinjiang, where Chinese anti-terror efforts had 
been criticized as heavy-handed before.
 

463
00:33:19,040 --> 00:33:23,160
Jiang’s time as leader was coming to an end, 
and it was time to elevate a successor. He chose  

464
00:33:23,160 --> 00:33:27,760
a rather obscure politician, Hu Jintao. 
Hu was the governor of Tibet for a time,  

465
00:33:27,760 --> 00:33:31,080
and was generally considered a fairly 
middle of the road, reliable, technocrat,  

466
00:33:31,080 --> 00:33:36,400
sort of like Jiang. He was a pretty low-profile, 
respected, safe choice. There were actually many  

467
00:33:36,400 --> 00:33:40,600
who wanted Jiang to remain as leader, beyond his 
allocated term, particularly from the military,  

468
00:33:40,600 --> 00:33:44,400
surprisingly. Jiang rejected these requests, 
stating how he thought it was important  

469
00:33:44,400 --> 00:33:48,640
for China to have a younger leader.
2002, the last full year of Jiang’s leadership,  

470
00:33:48,640 --> 00:33:52,840
was pretty uneventful. Mainly his time was spent 
dealing with the boring internal politics of the  

471
00:33:52,840 --> 00:33:57,240
change in leaders, with a few minor international 
trips. He got some of his ideas, most notably the  

472
00:33:57,240 --> 00:34:01,960
“Three Represents” written into the constitution. 
He stayed on as chairman of the Central Military  

473
00:34:01,960 --> 00:34:06,800
Commission until 2004, but his leadership 
was de facto over at the end of 2002.
 

474
00:34:06,800 --> 00:34:10,240
It was all rather unceremonious and 
abrupt, mostly done behind the scenes,  

475
00:34:10,240 --> 00:34:15,120
as is typical in Chinese history. Though, Jiang’s 
political career was not over, even in retirement.  

476
00:34:15,120 --> 00:34:19,200
He kept a modicum of influence through a group of 
of politicians generally known as the “Shanghai  

477
00:34:19,200 --> 00:34:23,280
clique” or “Shanghai gang.” I don’t want to get 
too into the weeds on this, trying to guess at the  

478
00:34:23,280 --> 00:34:27,200
inner workings of the Politburo in the last 30 
years is basically impossible. You’re better  

479
00:34:27,200 --> 00:34:30,760
off consulting a magic eight ball than some of 
these articles written about it, I swear.
 

480
00:34:30,760 --> 00:34:35,240
The TL; DR is the Shanghai gang was a bunch of 
Jiang’s friends who stayed on after he retired,  

481
00:34:35,240 --> 00:34:39,680
some notable members being Zhou Yongkang 
and Wang Huning. They had some minor clashes  

482
00:34:39,680 --> 00:34:44,400
with Hu Jintao, and the gang was generally 
broken up under Xi Jinping. What precisely  

483
00:34:44,400 --> 00:34:48,960
they did and affected is anyone’s guess.
Jiang kept a fairly low profile in retirement,  

484
00:34:48,960 --> 00:34:53,360
appearing occasionally at events and on 
holidays, mainly. But, he kept a very high  

485
00:34:53,360 --> 00:34:57,080
profile in the minds of many Chinese people, 
through the greatest internet meme of all:  

486
00:34:57,080 --> 00:35:01,840
toad culture. You can’t talk about Jiang Zemin 
without at least mentioning toad culture.
 

487
00:35:01,840 --> 00:35:05,800
Started as a joke about Jiang’s demeanor and his 
somewhat toad-like appearance, it has morphed  

488
00:35:05,800 --> 00:35:10,520
into a strange sort of counterculture. Hu 
Jintao’s and Xi Jinping’s terms both saw severe  

489
00:35:10,520 --> 00:35:14,400
curtailments of personal liberties and rights 
in China, creating a longing for the much more  

490
00:35:14,400 --> 00:35:17,960
hands-off era of Jiang Zemin.
There’s a ton of specific memes and  

491
00:35:17,960 --> 00:35:21,520
jokes as a part of toad culture. Some of my 
favorites are repeating some of Jiang’s more  

492
00:35:21,520 --> 00:35:26,520
ridiculous quotes, like “too simple, sometimes 
naive.” “True fans will always recognize him”  

493
00:35:26,520 --> 00:35:29,680
is another good one, regarding images of 
things that have a vague resemblance to  

494
00:35:29,680 --> 00:35:35,040
Jiang. Some other miscellaneous memes include 
referring to him as “the elder,” or “plus one  

495
00:35:35,040 --> 00:35:39,520
second,” wishing a long life to Jiang.
But, as we all as must learn, internet points  

496
00:35:39,520 --> 00:35:44,000
don’t matter much in real life, and Jiang 
Zemin passed away on November 30th, 2022,  

497
00:35:44,000 --> 00:35:49,480
at the age of 96. He was just a kid. Jiang Zemin 
was quite the guy, both as a person and as a  

498
00:35:49,480 --> 00:35:54,440
leader. He oversaw China’s meteoric rise in both 
economic terms, but also in scientific, cultural,  

499
00:35:54,440 --> 00:35:59,040
and military terms. While certainly not without 
controversy and scandal, he is remembered as a  

500
00:35:59,040 --> 00:36:02,960
steady hand, and as a personable guy.
He navigated crisis and instability,  

501
00:36:02,960 --> 00:36:07,800
and integrated Western-style capitalism with 
Chinese-style Marxism. His moderation and wisdom  

502
00:36:07,800 --> 00:36:11,560
saw China through a period that could have 
been incredibly destabilizing and dangerous.  

503
00:36:11,560 --> 00:36:15,000
He’s remembered for the relative openness 
and freedom of his time, when the Chinese  

504
00:36:15,000 --> 00:36:27,560
political sphere was full of hope and progress, 
rather than the tensions of the modern era.

